  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Increase S. Smith was glad to learn from Caroline Weston&apos;s letter, which was written after &quot;the meeting&quot; [of the Mass. Anti-Slavery Society], that the meeting &quot;terminated so favorably for the Mass. Board.&quot; He gives an enthusiastic account of the sermons delivered in Hingham by Dr. Charles Theodor C. Follen. Referring to resolutions passed at the convention of two (anti-slavery?) societies in Hingham, Increase S. Smith states that the Female Society is not recognized. He inquires about the real cause of the trouble between the American and the Massachusetts Societies; he believes that &quot;sectarian prejudice is the principal cause.&quot;</subfield>
